<H3> <TI>   Ministry Proposes Danube Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ministry Proposes Danube Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1105191794 Prague CTK in English 1827 GMT 11 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1105191794 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>Bratislava</LOCATION>, <DATE>May 11</DATE> (CTK) -- The <ORGANIZATION>Slovak Foreign 
Ministry</ORGANIZATION> reiterated its willingness to continue talks with 
<LOCATION>Budapest</LOCATION> on the division of the <ORGANIZATION>Danube</ORGANIZATION>'s waters between the 
Gabcikovo derivation canal on <LOCATION>Slovakia</LOCATION>'s territory and the 
<ORGANIZATION>Danube</ORGANIZATION>'s old course, in a note extended to the <ORGANIZATION>Hungarian Embassy</ORGANIZATION> 
today, the ministry told <ORGANIZATION>CTK</ORGANIZATION>. 
  The Ministry proposed that talks take place on <DATE>May 18-19</DATE> in 
<LOCATION>Bratislava</LOCATION>. "It is already the second date proposed by the 
ministry for talks on the temporary water regime on the river 
and it would therefore welcome it if the Hungarian side said it 
was ready for such talks," the note says. It says that such 
talks should help achieve goals proposed by the <ORGANIZATION>European Union</ORGANIZATION> 
(<ORGANIZATION>EU</ORGANIZATION>) experts. "It is necessary, however, to take into account 
the possibilities of technical realization and economic impact 
of individual solutions," the note says. 
  Beside the dispute over the Gabcikovo hydroelectric project 
itself which was taken to the <ORGANIZATION>International Court of Justice</ORGANIZATION> in 
<LOCATION>The Hague</LOCATION> <DATE>last July</DATE>, <LOCATION>Bratislava</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Budapest</LOCATION> are also in 
disagreement over the temporary water regime on the <LOCATION>Danube</LOCATION> to 
function until a verdict is passed in <LOCATION>The Hague</LOCATION>. 
  Hungary demands that <LOCATION>Slovakia</LOCATION> let more water to flow into 
the 
<LOCATION>Danube</LOCATION>'s old course even at the cost of restricting electricity 
production at <LOCATION>Gabcikovo</LOCATION>, while Slovak experts say that the 
improvement of the state of the <ORGANIZATION>Danube</ORGANIZATION>'s tributaries on the 
Hungarian side which are drying up does not so much depend on 
the flow of water but rather on the construction of the system 
of weirs which would raise the water level to such an extent as 
it flows also into the tributaries. However, the <ORGANIZATION>Hungarian 
Parliament</ORGANIZATION> rejected the construction of the weirs and decided to 
supply the tributaries with water with the help of pumps. An 
attempt to reach a compromise undertaken by <ORGANIZATION>EU Commission</ORGANIZATION> 
experts has so far failed. 
  Nevertheless, <LOCATION>Bratislava</LOCATION> made it clear it is willing to be 
accommodating when during a meeting of the two countries' 
environment ministers in mid-April in <LOCATION>Bratislava</LOCATION> <PERSON>Juraj Hrasko</PERSON> 
promised to his Hungarian counterpart to double the amount of 
water flowing through Mosoni-Duna tributary on Hungarian 
territory as of <DATE>May 15</DATE>. 

</TEXT>

