<H3> <TI>   Moravcik Discusses `Partnership,' Gabcikovo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0802182694 Prague CTK in English 1703 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0802182694 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <FÊP=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>Bratislava</LOCATION>, Feb 8 (CTK) -- Slovak Prime Minister 
<PERSON>Vladimir Meciar</PERSON> will sign a general document on <ORGANIZATION>NATO</ORGANIZATION>'s 
<ORGANIZATION>Partnership for Peace</ORGANIZATION> plan in <LOCATION>Brussels</LOCATION> on <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> [9 
<DATE>February</DATE>], Foreign Minister <PERSON>Jozef Moravcik</PERSON> confirmed today. 
  Moravcik also reported that the government approved a bill 
on 
the principles of the provisional water management regime at the 
Danube hydroelectric power station at Gabcikovo-Nagymaros, on 
the Slovak- Hungarian border. The bill is based on reports 
compiled by an expert group from the <ORGANIZATION>European Union</ORGANIZATION> (<ORGANIZATION>EU</ORGANIZATION>) 
commission and the two states involved in construction, <LOCATION>Slovakia</LOCATION> 
and <LOCATION>Hungary</LOCATION>. He said the government favors the provisional 
water management regime, as the Slovak section of the commission 
recommended. 
  <LOCATION>Slovakia</LOCATION> proposes that, at the beginning of the vegetation 
phase, the Danube branch be flooded while the current flow in 
the old riverbed is preserved, he said. 
  <PERSON>Moravcik</PERSON> stressed <LOCATION>Slovakia</LOCATION> fully respected Hungarian fears 
that too little water would be left in the <LOCATION>Danube</LOCATION> on Hungarian 
territory and would implement concrete measures to prevent this 
from happening. He added that in approving the bill the <ORGANIZATION>Slovak 
Government</ORGANIZATION> was making no comment on the original <DATE>1977</DATE> agreement 
on the construction of the dam and that any agreement on the 
water management regime would be valid only until the 
<ORGANIZATION>International Court of Justice</ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION>The Hague</LOCATION>, which is to settle 
the dispute between <LOCATION>Slovakia</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Hungary</LOCATION>, delivers its judgment. 

</TEXT>

