<H3> <TI>   Slovakia, Hungary Seek Ruling on Gabcikovo </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Slovakia, Hungary Seek Ruling on Gabcikovo </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0205153694 Prague CTK in English 1443 GMT 2 May 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0205153694 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Hague, <DATE>May 2</DATE> (CTK) -- <LOCATION>Slovakia</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Hungary</LOCATION> today 
officially submitted their dispute over the Gabcikovo-Nagymaros 
hydroelectric works to the <ORGANIZATION>International Court of Justice</ORGANIZATION>. 
  <LOCATION>Slovakia</LOCATION> accuses <LOCATION>Hungary</LOCATION> of not honoring the commitments it 
took on in the Czechoslovak-Hungarian agreement concluded in 
<DATE>September 1977</DATE>. <LOCATION>Budapest</LOCATION> blames <LOCATION>Bratislava</LOCATION> for undertaking 
unilateral steps, causing damage through restricting the flow in 
the <LOCATION>Danube</LOCATION>'s original bed and negatively affecting the 
environment, The court is also to evaluate whether or not the 
<DATE>1977</DATE> agreement is valid. 
  <LOCATION>Hungary</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Slovakia</LOCATION> decided to turn to the international 
court in <DATE>April 1993</DATE>, after their talks on the issue were 
stalemated. A commission of experts from the <ORGANIZATION>European Union</ORGANIZATION> 
(<ORGANIZATION>EU</ORGANIZATION>) worked out an objective analysis of the issue. 
  Documents containing the two sides' arguments were brought 
to 
the court in two fully-packed vans. 
  The agreement to present the dispute to the <ORGANIZATION>International 
Court of Justice</ORGANIZATION> was reached by the two countries quite 
smoothly. Today's behavior of both Hungarian and Slovak 
representatives indicated that the former tension between 
<LOCATION>Bratislava</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Budapest</LOCATION> has dwindled for the time being. The 
two countries also express their willingness to respect the 
court's decision. 
  However, the dispute is expected to drag on for long due to 
the controversial issue itself and the rightfulness of most 
arguments. The <ORGANIZATION>International Court</ORGANIZATION> will not decide on the 
problem before <DATE>1997</DATE>, as first it has to solve another six big 
disputes. 
  The idea of damming the <LOCATION>Danube</LOCATION> in its Slovak-Hungarian 
border 
section first appeared in <DATE>1910</DATE>. It was reappeared in <DATE>1950</DATE>, but 
the agreement on the construction of a giant project was signed 
between Czechoslovak and Hungarian communist regimes only on 
<DATE>September 15, 1977</DATE>. In <DATE>1989</DATE> the <ORGANIZATION>Hungarian Parliament</ORGANIZATION> and 
government began to distance themselves from the project and 
later decided to halt the construction of its Hungarian part in 
<LOCATION>Nagymaros</LOCATION>. <LOCATION>Slovakia</LOCATION> completed the hydroelectric waterworks in 
Gabcikovo in late <DATE>1992</DATE>. 

</TEXT>

