<H3> <TI>   Kovac Views Possible Reconciliation With Hungary </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kovac Views Possible Reconciliation With Hungary </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2706155094 Prague CTK in English 1432 GMT 27 Jun 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2706155094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>Bratislava</LOCATION> <DATE>June 27</DATE> (CTK) -- Slovak President <PERSON>Michal 
Kovac</PERSON> said it may be possible to withdraw the disputed case of 
the Gabcikovo hydroelectric power project on the Danube from the 
<ORGANIZATION>International Court of Justice</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>The Hague</LOCATION>. 
  If indeed a historical reconciliation has come about between 
<LOCATION>Slovakia</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Hungary</LOCATION>, consideration could also then be given to 
whether it would be "more advantageous" and "wiser" to withdraw 
the case and resolve it together, <PERSON>Kovac</PERSON> told journalists in 
<LOCATION>Bratislava</LOCATION> today. 
  <LOCATION>Slovakia</LOCATION> accuses <LOCATION>Hungary</LOCATION> of violating its commitments in an 
international agreement concerning the project in <DATE>1977</DATE>. <LOCATION>Hungary</LOCATION> 
accuses <LOCATION>Slovakia</LOCATION> of unilaterally deciding to divert the <LOCATION>River 
Danube</LOCATION> from its old course and of thereby causing great 
environmental damage. The case was taken to The Hague in <DATE>May</DATE>. 
  <PERSON>Kovac</PERSON> said he would test the possibility of a historical 
reconciliation on his visit to <LOCATION>Budapest</LOCATION> this <DATE>autumn</DATE>, on which he 
has been invited by Hungarian President <PERSON>Arpad Goncz</PERSON>. The two 
heads of state returned today from a visit to the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> 
during which they held talks with President <PERSON>Bill Clinton</PERSON> and 
received an award from the <ORGANIZATION>Institute for East-West Studies</ORGANIZATION> 
(IEWS) for their efforts in seeking a settlement between 
<LOCATION>Slovakia</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Hungary</LOCATION>. 
  On his visit to <PERSON>Hungary Kovac</PERSON> hopes to hold talks not only 
with <PERSON>Goncz</PERSON> but also with members of the new Hungarian 
Government, he said. Maybe then questions like the 
Gabcikovo-Nagymaros dam could be de-politicised and settled more 
easily, he said. 

</TEXT>

