<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Fails To Meet Deadline on Dam </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2101214194 Bratislava PRAVDA in Slovak 19 Jan 94 pp 1, 8 </F>
<F P=103> AU2101214194 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava PRAVDA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <FÊP=105> Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<FÊP=106> [Report by Jan Skoda: "Waiting Not for Water but for the </F>
Government"] 
  [Excerpts] On <DATE>Monday</DATE> [17 <DATE>January</DATE>], <LOCATION>Hungary</LOCATION> presented to 
the <ORGANIZATION>European Union</ORGANIZATION> [<ORGANIZATION>EU</ORGANIZATION>] headquarters in <LOCATION>Brussels</LOCATION> its official 
response to the <ORGANIZATION>EU</ORGANIZATION> experts' recommendation concerning the 
division of Danube water at Gabcikovo. This was announced by 
<PERSON>Gyorgy Tatar</PERSON>, Hungarian ministerial commissioner [title as 
published] for the Gabcikovo-Nagymaros hydroelectric power 
project. Tatar stated in the Hungarian daily NEPSZABADSAG that, 
while <LOCATION>Hungary</LOCATION> submitted its response by the <ORGANIZATION>EU</ORGANIZATION>'s deadline, the 
same allegedly cannot be said of <LOCATION>Slovakia</LOCATION>. 
  We have, therefore, contacted the Slovak mission at the <ORGANIZATION>EU</ORGANIZATION> 
headquarters in <LOCATION>Brussels</LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION>Ministry of Foreign Affairs</ORGANIZATION> in 
<LOCATION>Bratislava</LOCATION>. They confirmed to us that, in a letter at the 
beginning of the year, <LOCATION>Jan Lisuch</LOCATION>, state secretary at the 
<ORGANIZATION>Ministry of Foreign Affairs</ORGANIZATION>, asked <ORGANIZATION>EU</ORGANIZATION> mediator <PERSON>Pablo Benavidez</PERSON> 
to extend the original 15 <DATE>January</DATE> deadline, set for the 
Hungarian and Slovak sides to submit their responses, until the 
end of the month. He explained this request by the fact that 
the <ORGANIZATION>Slovak Government</ORGANIZATION> has been unable to discuss its standpoint 
so far. The standpoint had been prepared several times, but it 
was necessary to incorporate into it comments from individual 
government departments, which has delayed the whole process. 
According to <PERSON>Vladimir Cemez</PERSON>, PhD, from the <ORGANIZATION>Ministry of Foreign 
Affairs</ORGANIZATION>, the response was to be on the agenda of yesterday's 
meeting of the <ORGANIZATION>Slovak Government</ORGANIZATION>. According to our information, 
however, this did not happen. [passage omitted] 
  <LOCATION>Hungary</LOCATION> is now accusing us that a month and a half was not 
enough for us to assume a position on the <ORGANIZATION>EU</ORGANIZATION>'s recommendation 
concerning the temporary division of Danube waters. Gyorgy 
Tatar claims, moreover, that the Slovak attitude actually 
confirms our negative stand on the <ORGANIZATION>EU</ORGANIZATION> recommendation, which, 
according to Hungarian newspapers, proposes that <PERCENT>40 percent</PERCENT> of 
the Danube water remain in the river's original bed and that 
<LOCATION>Budapest</LOCATION> build two small dams on its territory. 
  In this affair, which may seem immaterial, we are, thus, 
once 
again in the position of the "evil" side that does not honor its 
commitments. Without trying to act as a judge, let us only 
observe that, this time, this is absolutely unnecessary. 

</TEXT>

