<H3> <TI>   Readiness To Negotiate Danube Division Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Readiness To Negotiate Danube Division Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0804200694 Prague CTK in English 1638 GMT 8 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0804200694 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>Bratislava</LOCATION>, <DATE>April 8</DATE> (CTK) -- A note sent today by 
the <ORGANIZATION>Slovak Foreign Ministry</ORGANIZATION> to the <ORGANIZATION>Hungarian Embassy</ORGANIZATION> in 
<LOCATION>Bratislava</LOCATION> expresses <LOCATION>Slovakia</LOCATION>'s readiness to resume as early as 
possible the talks on the establishment of a temporary water 
regime on the <LOCATION>Danube</LOCATION>. 
  The <ORGANIZATION>Slovak Ministry</ORGANIZATION> thus responded to a note from the 
<ORGANIZATION>Hungarian Foreign Ministry</ORGANIZATION> of <DATE>March 28</DATE>, in which <LOCATION>Budapest</LOCATION> urged 
the Slovak government to resume the negotiations immediately. 
The Hungarian note reacted to <LOCATION>Slovakia</LOCATION>'s rejection of a 
compromise proposal by <ORGANIZATION>European Union</ORGANIZATION> experts for the method of 
division of the <ORGANIZATION>Danube</ORGANIZATION>'s water between the original bed of the 
border river and a derivation canal built by <LOCATION>Bratislava</LOCATION> on 
Slovak territory. Budapest itself accepted the compromise 
proposal, though with reservations. 
  In opposition to this, the Slovak note recalls that the <ORGANIZATION>EU</ORGANIZATION> 
experts had also recommended to build weirs in the <LOCATION>Danube</LOCATION>'s 
original bed to prevent drying up of some river's branches, but 
the Hungarian parliament recently rejected the weirs' 
construction. Nevertheless, in its document <LOCATION>Bratislava</LOCATION> says it 
favors further search for a rational and effective solution to 
the problem. 

</TEXT>

