<HEAD>Police Help 2,000 Protest Danube Power Project</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police stood by peacefully as about
2,000 people protested a <LOCATION>Danube River</LOCATION> power project, a sign of
Communist authorities' increasing tolerance of dissent that does
not challenge them directly.
   A participant in <DATE>Friday</DATE>'s demonstration said police refrained
from interfering and even cleared the way for marchers as they
wound their way through downtown <LOCATION>Budapest</LOCATION> to the <ORGANIZATION>Austrian Embassy</ORGANIZATION>.
   The project in <LOCATION>Nagymaros</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Hungary</LOCATION>, is being financed largely by
<LOCATION>Austria</LOCATION>.
   The marcher, who spoke on condition of anonymity, called it an
unusual sign of police cooperation with the young members of the
unofficial <ORGANIZATION>Danube Circle</ORGANIZATION> ecological group.
   State-run television also took the unusual step of running,
without comment, a one-minute film segment on its main evening
newscast showing protesters arriving at the embassy.
   Among them was biologist <PERSON>Janos Varga</PERSON>, a leader of the ecologists.
   The marchers carried placards and banners demanding a halt to
the project, a joint venture involving hydropower installations on
the Danube at Gabcikovo in <LOCATION>Czechoslovakia</LOCATION> and at <LOCATION>Nagymaros</LOCATION>.
   Banners read ``We Want Clear Water,'' ``No Dams'' and ``We Want
Our Danube.''
   Hungarian and Austrian ecologists have said that damming the
<LOCATION>Danube</LOCATION> and slowing its flow will threaten drinking water reserves
of millions of Hungarians and destroy large areas of riverside
forestland in both <LOCATION>Hungary</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Czechsolovakia</LOCATION>.
   Under an Austrian-Hungarian contract signed on <DATE>May 29, 1986</DATE>,
Austrian companies will carry out <PERCENT>70 percent</PERCENT> of the <MONEY>$483 million</MONEY>
worth of construction work.
   A delegation of four was allowed to enter the embassy to hand
over a resolution protesting <LOCATION>Austria</LOCATION>'s financial participation,
<ORGANIZATION>Austria Press Agency</ORGANIZATION> reported.
   It said the Austrian ambassador was not there but promised the
protesters by telephone a written reply to their plea.
</TEXT>
