<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Summary] <LOCATION>Ukraine</LOCATION> became a member of the <ORGANIZATION>Commonwealth of 
Danube Lands</ORGANIZATION> [<ORGANIZATION>Spivdruzhnist Dunayskykh Zemel</ORGANIZATION>] on 23 <DATE>June</DATE>. A 
session of the <ORGANIZATION>Commonwealth</ORGANIZATION> took place near <LOCATION>Budapest</LOCATION> on 23 <DATE>June</DATE>, 
where <LOCATION>Ukraine</LOCATION> was represented by <LOCATION>Odessa Oblast</LOCATION>. The issues of 
losses caused by <ORGANIZATION>UN</ORGANIZATION> sanctions against former <LOCATION>Yugoslavia</LOCATION>, the 
economy, the environment, and joint action by Danube lands in 
the areas of sport and tourism were examined at the session. 
Delegations from <LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Austria</LOCATION>, the Czech and <ORGANIZATION>Slovak 
Republics</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Romania</LOCATION>, and <LOCATION>Bulgaria</LOCATION> took part. 
  <PERSON>Ruslan Bodelan</PERSON>, people's deputy of <LOCATION>Ukraine</LOCATION> and chairman of 
<ORGANIZATION>Odessa Oblast Council</ORGANIZATION>, who headed the Ukrainian delegation, said 
at <LOCATION>Budapest</LOCATION> airport: "This is another step toward our state's 
claim to the possibility of resolving issues jointly with our 
counterparts, with other countries. This especially concerns 
use of the Danube artery as a river, along which cargoes can and 
should be transported with the help of our <ORGANIZATION>Danube Shipping 
Company</ORGANIZATION>. It is about resolving problems of the ecological state 
of the <LOCATION>Danube</LOCATION>, preserving our reservations and national parks, 
and developing national culture and national traditions." 

</TEXT>

