<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 92 / EC tries to defuse Danube dispute
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NICHOLAS DENTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BUDAPEST
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE <ORGANIZATION>European Community</ORGANIZATION> has stepped in to avert confrontation between <LOCATION>Hungary</LOCATION>
and <LOCATION>Slovakia</LOCATION> over the damming of the river <LOCATION>Danube</LOCATION>. The move comes as
Slovakian constructors are poised to block and divert the <LOCATION>Danube</LOCATION> river into
the controversial Gabcikovo power plant against furious Hungarian
opposition.
The <ORGANIZATION>EC</ORGANIZATION> has invited Slovak and Hungarian negotiators to meet today in
<LOCATION>Brussels</LOCATION> to try to hammer out a compromise.
The <ORGANIZATION>EC</ORGANIZATION>'s initiative in hosting last-minute talks put on hold <LOCATION>Slovakia</LOCATION>'s plan
to begin damming the river yesterday but the delay represents only a stay of
execution and the chances for agreement remain slim. The <ORGANIZATION>EC</ORGANIZATION> environment
commissioner, <PERSON>Mr Karel Van Miert</PERSON>, had urged <LOCATION>Slovakia</LOCATION> to avoid taking an
irreversible step to complete the project before negotiations but made no
further intervention.
Both sides have painted themselves into a corner, with <LOCATION>Budapest</LOCATION> claiming
that the 40km diversion of the <LOCATION>Danube</LOCATION>, its northern border, would be an
environmental catastrophe and territorial violation. <LOCATION>Slovakia</LOCATION>'s position is
equally hard, because of the economic cost of abandoning the project.
The dispute has become entangled with tensions over the 800,000 Hungarian
minority in <LOCATION>Slovakia</LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
