<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of people
exercised their new freedom <DATE>Saturday</DATE> by forming a 100-mile human
chain to protest a hydroelectric dam project on the <LOCATION>Danube River</LOCATION>,
the government news agency said.
   The <ORGANIZATION>CTK</ORGANIZATION> news agency said 100,000 people from <LOCATION>Czechoslovakia</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Hungary</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Austria</LOCATION> formed the chain across territory in all three
nations.
   Meanwhile, thousands of West Germans and Czechoslovak citizens
formed a 2.5-mile human chain across their common border in a
gesture of triumph over the waning divisions between East and West,
<ORGANIZATION>CTK</ORGANIZATION> said.
   Tens of thousands of them passed through the border crossing
where the chain was formed, drawing attention to the ``absurdity of
the Iron Curtain,'' <ORGANIZATION>CTK</ORGANIZATION> said.
   Hard-line Communist regimes have been replaced by reformist
governments in <LOCATION>Czechoslovakia</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Hungary</LOCATION> in the past two years
that have opened their borders with the <LOCATION>West</LOCATION>. While much of <LOCATION>Eastern
Europe</LOCATION>'s ``Iron Curtain'' has been torn down, the continent remains
divided by the <ORGANIZATION>NATO</ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION>Warsaw</LOCATION> Pact military alliances.
   Among those taking part was <LOCATION>Czechoslovakia</LOCATION>'s foreign minister,
former dissident <PERSON>Jiri Dienstbier</PERSON>. He was quoted as saying that a
joint commmission to discuss the opening of new border crossings
between the two countries would meet next week.
   In the hydroelectric dam protest, <ORGANIZATION>CTK</ORGANIZATION> said that up to 100,000
people helped form a human chain along the <LOCATION>Danube</LOCATION> over a span of
about 100 miles from the town of <LOCATION>Hainburg</LOCATION> in <LOCATION>Austria</LOCATION>, across to
<LOCATION>Bratislava</LOCATION> in <LOCATION>Czechoslovakia</LOCATION> and to <LOCATION>Komarom</LOCATION> in <LOCATION>Hungary</LOCATION>.
   <LOCATION>Hungary</LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Parliament</ORGANIZATION> already voted to scrap its part of the
joint dam project with <LOCATION>Czechoslovakia</LOCATION>, and the new <LOCATION>Prague</LOCATION>
leadership has said it will review the environmental consequences
of its part of the power plant at Gabcikovo.
   Activists read aloud a letter addressed to Czechoslovak
President <PERSON>Vaclav Havel</PERSON>, requesting his support for the demands that
the project be stopped, <ORGANIZATION>MTI</ORGANIZATION> reported. Participants also called for
<LOCATION>Austria</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Hungary</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Czechoslovakia</LOCATION> to create a nature reserve
along the <LOCATION>Danube</LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION>MTI</ORGANIZATION> said.
   In the Hungarian town of <LOCATION>Visegrad</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Andras Szekfue</PERSON> of the
<ORGANIZATION>Hungarian Green Party</ORGANIZATION> told about 100 people that since the
Hungarian part of the project at Nagymaros had been scrapped, they
must help the Czechoslovaks stop the dam at <LOCATION>Gabcikovo</LOCATION>, a
participant told <ORGANIZATION>The Associated Press</ORGANIZATION>.
   
   Referring to the democratic revolutions that have swept the <LOCATION>East</LOCATION>
bloc, Szekfue added: ``The good thing is that we no longer need to
work in secret but can pursue our aims with democratic means.''
   In the Hungarian city of <LOCATION>Esztergom</LOCATION>, activist <PERSON>Csaba Paska</PERSON> noted,
``the Danube links the people (of the three countries), and this
dam which divides us was the work of politicians.''
   Among placards and banners carried by protesters was one
reading, ``Build bridges, not dams.''
   Austrian and Hungarian environmentalists had long opposed the
mammoth project, maintaining it would destroy unique wildlife and
have other irreparable consequences for the <LOCATION>Danube</LOCATION>.
   The project was agreed on by the Communist governments in <LOCATION>Prague</LOCATION>
and <LOCATION>Budapest</LOCATION> in the <DATE>1970s</DATE>. <LOCATION>Austria</LOCATION> had agreed to finance part of
the Hungarian project in exchange for electricity.
   The chain across the West German-Czechoslovak border was formed
between the Czechoslovak town of <PERSON>Zlezna Ruda</PERSON> and the West German
border town of <LOCATION>Bayrisch Eisenstein</LOCATION>, about 100 miles northeast of
<LOCATION>Munich</LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
