<H3> <TI>   Moravcik on Expectations of Hungarian Socialists </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Moravcik on Expectations of Hungarian Socialists </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU3005180994 Prague CTK in English 1628 GMT 30 May 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU3005180994 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>Bratislava</LOCATION> <DATE>May 30</DATE> (CTK) -- Slovak Premier <PERSON>Jozef 
Moravcik</PERSON> said <DATE>today</DATE> he expected the Hungarian socialists of 
<PERSON>Gyula Horn</PERSON>, who have won the parliamentary elections, to pursue 
a pragmatic policy, which could produce a relatively quick 
settlement of pending problems between <LOCATION>Bratislava</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Budapest</LOCATION>. 
<PERSON>Moravcik</PERSON> met Horn during his visit to <LOCATION>Bratislava</LOCATION> before the 
elections. 
  <PERSON>Nevertheless Moravcik</PERSON>, who was optimistic about chances of a 
Slovak-Hungarian dialogue when he came to power in mid-March, 
said he did not expect a basic inter-state treaty to be 
concluded before the parliamentary elections which will end his 
cabinet's term. Early elections are to be held on <DATE>September 30</DATE> 
and <DATE>October 1</DATE>. 
  "It cannot be expected that the whole process of 
preparation, 
conclusion, signing and ratification of the basic treaty of good 
neighbourly relations could be managed within such a short time 
span. This is technically entirely ruled out, but we can take 
important steps to this effect," <PERSON>Moravcik</PERSON> said. 
  <LOCATION>Bratislava</LOCATION> hopes the treaty will confirm the existing border 
between <LOCATION>Slovakia</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Hungary</LOCATION>, which were set by international 
conferences following World War One and which have been 
challenged by certain forces in <LOCATION>Hungary</LOCATION>. 
  <LOCATION>Budapest</LOCATION> on the other hand hopes for an extension of the 
rights of the Hungarian ethnic minority in <LOCATION>Slovakia</LOCATION>. Some 
560,000 ethnic Hungarians live <LOCATION>Slovakia</LOCATION>, constituting about <PERCENT>11 
percent</PERCENT> of its total population. 
  The two countries are also facing other pending problems, 
such as the a dispute over the Gabcikovo hydroproject on the 
<LOCATION>Danube</LOCATION>, discords over the temporary division of the Danube 
waters, non-existence of a readmission agreement and the opening 
of new border crossings which <LOCATION>Slovakia</LOCATION> conditions by the 
conclusion of the readmission agreement. 

</TEXT>

