  [Text] <LOCATION>Budapest</LOCATION>, 22 <DATE>March</DATE> (MTI) -- "The event of the day 
is in the parliament," Foreign Affairs Spokesman <PERSON>Janos Herman</PERSON> 
told the press on <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> [22 <DATE>March</DATE>], referring to the <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> 
morning plenary session on <LOCATION>Hungary</LOCATION>'s application for membership 
of the <ORGANIZATION>European Union</ORGANIZATION>. 
  In view of the defective Gabcikovo sluice chambers, the 
<ORGANIZATION>Hungarian Government</ORGANIZATION> has called on countries which insist on the 
principle of free navigation on the <LOCATION>Danube</LOCATION>, which conduct 
shipping traffic on the river, and which signed the <DATE>1948</DATE> 
<ORGANIZATION>Belgrade Convention</ORGANIZATION> on the <ORGANIZATION>Order of Navigation</ORGANIZATION>, to warn the 
<ORGANIZATION>Slovak Government</ORGANIZATION> to immediately stop the law-breaking action 
and ensure free passage, <PERSON>Herman</PERSON> said. He drew attention to the 
<ORGANIZATION>Slovak Government</ORGANIZATION>'s responsibility for the cessation of shipping 
on the Danube due to a technical and professional error. 
  After the first sluice chamber accident, the <ORGANIZATION>Hungarian 
Government</ORGANIZATION> warned the <ORGANIZATION>Slovak Government</ORGANIZATION> of the possibility of 
the second chamber going wrong, and asked it to do its best to 
make the given river section navigable. There was no Slovak 
response to this request, <PERSON>Herman</PERSON> said. 
  Answering a question, the spokesman said that the building 
of 
version "C," and thus the recent accident, was to be blamed on 
former Slovak Governments, while <LOCATION>Hungary</LOCATION> would welcome possible 
negotiations with the new Slovak cabinet on boosting bilateral 
links. 
  Herman reported fair progress in preparations for a 
"supervisory" conference of the <DATE>1992</DATE> <ORGANIZATION>Helsinki Conference on 
Security and Cooperation</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION>, to be held in <LOCATION>Budapest</LOCATION>'s 
Convention Center from <DATE>October 10</DATE> to <DATE>December 2</DATE>, and subsequent 
summit meetings from <DATE>December 5-6</DATE>. 
  He finally announced the <DATE>March 24</DATE> visit to <LOCATION>Hungary</LOCATION> of <PERSON>Peter 
Tarnoff</PERSON>, deputy undersecretary of state in charge of East 
European affairs at the <ORGANIZATION>U.S. State Department</ORGANIZATION>, who will study 
the region's situation and discuss <ORGANIZATION>NATO</ORGANIZATION>'s Partnership for Peace. 

</TEXT>

