<FÊP=106> [Report by <PERSON>Heorhiy Vorotnyuk</PERSON> from <LOCATION>Odessa</LOCATION>: "A New Competitor </F>
on the Danube?"] 
  [Text] According to the Moldovan mass media, the 
government of that country does everything possible to promote 
the creation of its own merchant fleet on the <LOCATION>Danube</LOCATION>. For that 
purpose, not only are negotiations conducted with the <ORGANIZATION>CIS</ORGANIZATION> 
countries on the fair division of the former <ORGANIZATION>Union</ORGANIZATION>'s fleet, but 
possibilities are also sought to purchase, build, and charter 
vessels. A shipping company -- "<LOCATION>Moldova</LOCATION> Shipping Company" -- 
was recently created there. It already has seven vessels at its 
disposal: three passenger ships, three freight vessels, and a 
barge. All of them have been chartered from Romanian ship 
owners and are, for the time being, kept in the Romanian port of 
<LOCATION>Constanta</LOCATION>. However, in the near future, our neighbors will 
start building a port on the <LOCATION>Danube</LOCATION>, where the Moldovan 
territory is adjacent to the river. 
  It looks like the <ORGANIZATION>Ukrainian Danube Shipping Company</ORGANIZATION> will 
have 
yet another competitor. At any rate, it will take care of the 
cargo from <LOCATION>Moldova</LOCATION> itself. 

</TEXT>

